PyDoc_STRVAR(__pyx_doc_6CMR_IA_3CMR___init__, "\n        Initializes a CMR object and prepares it to simulate the session defined by pres_mat. [Modified]\n\n        :param params: Dictionary of model parameters and settings for the simulation. Use CMR_IA.make_params() to get a template dictionary.\n        :param pres_mat: 2D array specifying the ID numbers of words presented to the model on each trial. Row i, column j holds the ID number of the jth word on the ith trial. ID numbers range from 1 to N (number of words in sem_mat). 0s are treated as padding and ignored. If presenting word pairs, use a 3D array with the length of the third dimension equals to 2.\n        :param sem_mat: 2D array of pairwise semantic similarities between all words in the word pool. The order of words must match the word ID numbers, with scores for word k located along row k-1 and column k-1.\n        :param source_mat: 3D array of source features for each presented word. One row per trial, one column per serial position, and the third dimension for the number of source features. Cell (i, j, k) contains the kth source feature of the jth item on list i. If None, no source features are used.\n        :param rec_mat: 2D array of ID numbers of words recalled by real subjects in a free recall phase on each trial. Rows correspond to pres_mat.\n        :param ffr_mat: 1D array of ID numbers of words recalled by real subjects in a final free recall phase.\n        :param cue_mat: 1D array of ID numbers of words presented to the model in recognition and cued recall. If presenting word pairs, use a 2D array with the length of the second dimension equals to 2.\n        :param task: String indicating the type of task to simulate. 'FR': free recall; 'CR': cued recall; 'Recog': recognition; 'Success': successive tests.\n        :param mode: String indicating the task mode to simulate.\n            - For 'FR': 'IFR' (immediate free recall), 'DFR' (delayed recall).\n            - For 'CR': 'Final' (cued recall in final stage).\n            - For 'Re""cog': 'Continuous' (continuous recognition), 'Hockley' (Hockley's variation of continuous recognition), 'Final' (recognition in final stage).\n            - For 'Success': 'Recog-CR' (test1 recognition, test2 cued recall), 'Recog-Recog' (test1 & test2 both recognition), 'CR-Recog' (test1 cued recall, test2 recognition), 'CR-CR' (test1 & test2 both cued recall).\n        :param test1_num: Integer indicating the number of items tested in test1 during successive tests.\n        ");

 0081:         """
 0082:         Initializes a CMR object and prepares it to simulate the session defined by pres_mat. [Modified]
 0083: 
 0084:         :param params: Dictionary of model parameters and settings for the simulation. Use CMR_IA.make_params() to get a template dictionary.
 0085:         :param pres_mat: 2D array specifying the ID numbers of words presented to the model on each trial. Row i, column j holds the ID number of the jth word on the ith trial. ID numbers range from 1 to N (number of words in sem_mat). 0s are treated as padding and ignored. If presenting word pairs, use a 3D array with the length of the third dimension equals to 2.
 0086:         :param sem_mat: 2D array of pairwise semantic similarities between all words in the word pool. The order of words must match the word ID numbers, with scores for word k located along row k-1 and column k-1.
 0087:         :param source_mat: 3D array of source features for each presented word. One row per trial, one column per serial position, and the third dimension for the number of source features. Cell (i, j, k) contains the kth source feature of the jth item on list i. If None, no source features are used.
 0088:         :param rec_mat: 2D array of ID numbers of words recalled by real subjects in a free recall phase on each trial. Rows correspond to pres_mat.
 0089:         :param ffr_mat: 1D array of ID numbers of words recalled by real subjects in a final free recall phase.
 0090:         :param cue_mat: 1D array of ID numbers of words presented to the model in recognition and cued recall. If presenting word pairs, use a 2D array with the length of the second dimension equals to 2.
 0091:         :param task: String indicating the type of task to simulate. 'FR': free recall; 'CR': cued recall; 'Recog': recognition; 'Success': successive tests.
 0092:         :param mode: String indicating the task mode to simulate.
 0093:             - For 'FR': 'IFR' (immediate free recall), 'DFR' (delayed recall).
 0094:             - For 'CR': 'Final' (cued recall in final stage).
 0095:             - For 'Recog': 'Continuous' (continuous recognition), 'Hockley' (Hockley's variation of continuous recognition), 'Final' (recognition in final stage).
 0096:             - For 'Success': 'Recog-CR' (test1 recognition, test2 cued recall), 'Recog-Recog' (test1 & test2 both recognition), 'CR-Recog' (test1 cued recall, test2 recognition), 'CR-CR' (test1 & test2 both cued recall).
 0097:         :param test1_num: Integer indicating the number of items tested in test1 during successive tests.
 0098:         """

Options are provided to update context and the model's associative matrices after presentation. [Modified]\n\n        :param item_idx: Index of the cell within the feature vector to be activated by the presented item.\n        :param source: If None, no source features are activated. If False, use the old context vector (used in CMR2).\n        ");

[Unchanged from CMR2]\n\n        :param time_limit: Simulated duration of the recall period in milliseconds. Determines the number of cycles of the leaky accumulator before the recall period ends.\n        :param max_recalls: Maximum number of retrievals (not overt recalls) the model is allowed to make. If this limit is reached, the recall period ends early. This setting prevents the model from consuming excessive runtime if its parameters cause it to make numerous recalls per trial.\n        ");

[Unchanged from CMR2]\n\n    :param params: Dictionary of model parameters and settings for the simulation. Use CMR_IA.make_params() to get a template dictionary.\n    :param pres_mat: 2D array specifying the ID numbers of words presented to the model on each trial. Row i, column j holds the ID number of the jth word on the ith trial. ID numbers range from 1 to N (number of words in sem_mat). 0s are treated as padding and ignored, allowing zero-padding for varying list lengths.\n    :param sem_mat: 2D array of pairwise semantic similarities between all words in the word pool. The order of words must match the word ID numbers, with scores for word k located along row k-1 and column k-1.\n    :param source_mat: 3D array of source features for each presented word if not None. One row per trial, one column per serial position, and the third dimension for the number of source features. Cell (i, j, k) contains the kth source feature of the jth item on list i.\n    :param mode: String indicating the type of free recall to simulate. 'IFR' for immediate free recall or 'DFR' for delayed recall.\n\n    :returns: Two 2D arrays. The first contains the ID numbers of items the model recalled on each trial. The second contains the response times of each item relative to the start of the recall period.\n    ");

 1296:     """
 1297:     Simulates a single session of free recall using the specified parameter set. [Unchanged from CMR2]
 1298: 
 1299:     :param params: Dictionary of model parameters and settings for the simulation. Use CMR_IA.make_params() to get a template dictionary.
 1300:     :param pres_mat: 2D array specifying the ID numbers of words presented to the model on each trial. Row i, column j holds the ID number of the jth word on the ith trial. ID numbers range from 1 to N (number of words in sem_mat). 0s are treated as padding and ignored, allowing zero-padding for varying list lengths.
 1301:     :param sem_mat: 2D array of pairwise semantic similarities between all words in the word pool. The order of words must match the word ID numbers, with scores for word k located along row k-1 and column k-1.
 1302:     :param source_mat: 3D array of source features for each presented word if not None. One row per trial, one column per serial position, and the third dimension for the number of source features. Cell (i, j, k) contains the kth source feature of the jth item on list i.
 1303:     :param mode: String indicating the type of free recall to simulate. 'IFR' for immediate free recall or 'DFR' for delayed recall.
 1304: 
 1305:     :returns: Two 2D arrays. The first contains the ID numbers of items the model recalled on each trial. The second contains the response times of each item relative to the start of the recall period.

[Unchanged from CMR2]\n\n    :param params: Dictionary of model parameters and settings for the simulation. Use CMR_IA.make_params() to get a template dictionary.\n    :param pres_mat: 2D array specifying the ID numbers of words presented to the model on each trial. Row i, column j holds the ID number of the jth word on the ith trial. ID numbers range from 1 to N (number of words in sem_mat). 0s are treated as padding and ignored, allowing zero-padding for varying list lengths.\n    :param identifiers: 1D array of session numbers, subject IDs, or other values indicating how the rows/trials in pres_mat and source_mat should be divided into sessions. For example, to simulate two four-trial sessions, set identifiers to np.array([0, 0, 0, 0, 1, 1, 1, 1]), indicating the latter four trials are from a different session than the first four.\n    :param sem_mat: 2D array of pairwise semantic similarities between all words in the word pool. The order of words must match the word ID numbers, with scores for word k located along row k-1 and column k-1.\n    :param source_mat: 3D array of source features for each presented word if not None. One row per trial, one column per serial position, and the third dimension for the number of source features. Cell (i, j, k) contains the kth source feature of the jth item on list i.\n    :param mode: String indicating the type of free recall to simulate. 'IFR' for immediate free recall or 'DFR' for delayed recall.\n\n    :returns: Two 2D arrays. The first contains the ID numbers of items the model recalled on each trial. The second contains the response times of each item relative to the start of the recall period.\n    ");

[Newly added]\n\n    :param params: Dictionary of model parameters and settings for the simulation. The order of words must match the word ID numbers, with scores for word k located along row k-1 and column k-1.\n    :param source_mat: If None, source coding will not be used (as in the paper).\n    \n    :returns: \n    - df_thin: Dataframe with columns \"session\", \"list\", and \"test_itemno\" in df_test plus three additional columns: \"s_resp\" (simulated response), \"s_rt\" (simulated reaction time, not used in the paper), and \"c_sim\" (context similarity for intrusion filtering).\n    - f_in_acc: List of Arrays of f_in for cued recalls (for developers).\n    - f_in_dif: List of Arrays of f_in minus retrieval threshold for cued recalls (for developers).\n    ");
